description:
Jeff Zoet is a photographer, director, editor, designer & cinematographer living in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.

Jeff strives to bring a refreshingly unique style and personality to the world of portrait photography, creating visually interesting photographs that combine all of his creative background and imagination. His specialty is creating complex composites using various sources and lighting techniques to produce dynamic imagery not limited to the constraints of reality.

Jeff views his photography as an always-improving endeavor, and continually pushes to outdo himself and amaze even those closest to him.

His last name is pronounced "Zoot", and literally translates to the word "sweet" in Dutch.
name: Jeff Zoet

description:
Hushicho is a comic creator who works independently and is best known for his long-running work Incubus Tales, which at time of writing is the longest-running comic of its type still running.

History

Growing up in a household that moved around constantly, Hushicho was exposed to a wide variety of sequential art, which influenced his style and philosophy for storytelling. Some of the series he loved the most growing up include Wonder Woman, Saint Seiya, and Docteur Justice.

During the first years of his professional career, he worked both in Japanese doujinshi, mainly behind the scenes and assisting, and also worked part-time assisting American comic professionals.

He did a few casual side comics, including a twice-weekly comic strip that ran for several years, at first, incorporating some input from dedicated readers into the light fantasy tale. However, when his partner of 7 years suddenly passed away, he worked the cheerful comic to a stopping point and then subsequently withdrew from any public appearances for a time.

Later in 2007, Incubus Tales was launched and proved to be his most enduring series. An adult-oriented satire, it has on several occasions included various types of social and even political commentary and creative critique. The comic has been collected into over 5 separate print editions.

During that same year, Hushicho met with Tsutsumi and formed Cornucopia Studios, a unifying studio for their collaborative work. Tsutsumi would later begin publishing Praying For Obsolescence, his science-fiction epic, after the two collaborated directly on a series called The Medium Men, which ran until 2008.

In 2010, Hushicho launched Lamia, an homage to Italian comics from decades past, and featuring a different sort of main cast from the familiar Incubus Tales. Lamia was collected into two comics to date and is currently on hiatus pending a third story.

Other series, such as Midnight Down, have turned up numerous times during his career but were less successful and popular, and so have never enjoyed a print collection.

The latest project from Hushicho is Witchbro, a uniquely all-ages series of vignettes depicting the life of a magical superhero at the beginning of his career in heroics. It was collected into a single comic.

Influences

Hushicho cites the art nouveau movement as his greatest influence, with artists such as Rackham, Beardsley, and Mucha. He also has stated admiration for a number of iconic illustrators such as Mizuki Shigeru and Maxfield Parrish, as well as a number of others including legendary comic artist Nick Cardy.

Views

Hushicho has often stated his belief that independent comics are the future of the medium, and he does not disguise his contempt for industry giants like Marvel and DC.

He has little patience for censorship, most especially censorship he views as arbitrary, and part of his reason for doing so much mature work is due to that fact.

Last but not least, he has repeatedly mentioned his disdain for writers who feel that the only way to convey high stakes is to kill off characters.

Heroes

Hushicho's favorite period of superhero comics is the Bronze Age which, according to him, was neither the "toss out every idea and see what sticks" attitude of the Golden Age, nor the uncertain footing of the Silver Age, but a better balance.

Among his favorite comics of all time are Justice League of America v1 #189 and 190, which boast striking covers by illustrator Brian Bolland. They feature probably Hushicho's favorite antagonist of the Justice League, the alien starfish known as Starro.

The villains he always enjoyed the most have always been strange and outlandish, such as Starro, Egg Fu, and MODOK.
name: Hushicho

Aniz Ansari is a writer & formerly an Assistant Editor for DC Comics Digital.

His work for DC included editorial work for Batman: The Jiro Kuwata Batmanga, Batman '66, Injustice: Gods Among Us, Batman: Arkham Origins, Scooby Doo, and He-Man & the Masters of the Universe.
name: Aniz Ansari

description: James Heath Lantz is a freelance writer who was heavily influenced by television, film, old time radio shows and books - especially comic books - growing up in Ohio. He's co-authored Roy Thomas Presents Captain Video with Roy Thomas. He also wrote the introductions for Pre-Code Classics: Weird Mysteries Volumes One and Two and Roy Thomas Presents Sheena - Queen of the Jungle Volume Three. (All published by PS Artbooks.) He is a staff writer for TwoMorrows Publishing's magazine Back Issue James currently lives in Italy with his wife Laura and their family of cats, dogs, a turtle and humans from Italy, Japan and the United States.
name: James Heath Lantz
